riting career to share his fitness passion with the world.</span></p></div></div></div></section><section data-section-id="pf-2fcc" data-pf-type="FlexSection" class="sc-gKlDTn jrBPeP pf-20_ pf-container-1"><div class="sc-jRGIGG bMuAgN pf-flex-section"><img alt="dumbbell push up" src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=2048" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=375 375w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=550 550w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=768 768w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=1024 1024w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=1280 1280w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=1440 1440w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=1680 1680w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=1800 1800w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=1920 1920w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/mariah-krafft.jpg?v=1772763864&width=2048 2048w" fetchPriority="low" decoding="async" loading="lazy" style="--pf-image-ratio:1.9470426409903714" sizes="75vw" data-pf-type="Image5" class="sc-fscnvs dncZrx pf-21_" store="[object Object]"/></div></section><section data-section-id="pf-1a9d" data-pf-type="FlexSection" class="sc-gKlDTn jrBPeP pf-22_ pf-container-1"><div class="sc-jRGIGG bMuAgN pf-flex-section"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cyRdfs qmQNK pf-23_"><strong>Why Chest Training Is a Must</strong></h2><p class="sc-hgRQsa gNGIPQ pf-25_" data-pf-type="Paragraph4"><input type="checkbox" id="compact-1a9d90b6-74c4-4e57-9ff0-47769daf8732"/><span class="pf-paragraph-content ">A bench is a valuable addition to any home gym. Yet you don't need a bench to get a great chest workout. Most people assume heavy pressing equipment is required to build a strong, defined chest — that is simply not the case. With nothing but <u><a href="https://www.ativafit.com/collections/adjustable-dumbbells" target="_blank"><span style="color: rgb(245, 166, 35);">a pair of dumbbells</span></a></u> and the floor beneath your feet, you're able to work all your pec fibers for maximum growth. Adjustable dumbbells like the <a href="/products/27-5-lbs-adjustable-weight-dumbbell" target="_self"><u><span style="color: rgb(245, 166, 35);">Ativafit Spark 27.5 Lb Adjustable Dumbbell Set</span></u></a> make it easy to increase resistance without cluttering your space.  Personal trainer Steve Theunissen has been coaching clients in home gyms for over 35 years, and the 11 exercises below — covering every angle of the chest — are drawn directly from that experience. But only if you know which exercises to do.<br><br>In this article, I'll lay out eleven dumbbell chest exercises you can do at home without a bench.<br><br>Before you dive into any workout, understand this: your chest muscles power critical daily moves — pushing doors, lifting groceries, carrying kids — so a stronger chest makes every day easier. On top of that, well-developed pecs:<br><strong><br>- Improve Posture:</strong> Pull your shoulders back, ease spine stress<br><strong>- Enhance Appearance:</strong> Create a balanced, confident silhouette<br><br>Ready to build more strength, better posture and a boost in confidence? Start your chest-focused routine today.</span></p></div></section><section data-section-id="pf-53a6" data-pf-type="FlexSection" class="sc-gKlDTn jrBPeP pf-28_ pf-container-1"><div class="sc-jRGIGG bMuAgN pf-flex-section"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cyRdfs qmQNK pf-29_"><strong>Muscles Worked in These Chest Exercises</strong></h2><p class="sc-hgRQsa gNGIPQ pf-31_" data-pf-type="Paragraph4"><input type="checkbox" id="compact-8d53a6d1-bd6a-48cf-b5fb-0b1c72947b9e"/><span class="pf-paragraph-content ">Your chest is made up of two muscles: the pectoralis major — the large, fan-shaped muscle covering the upper chest — and the pectoralis minor, which sits beneath it. The pec major is responsible for most of the pushing strength you develop during pressing and fly movements.Supporting muscles engaged in every exercise below include the anterior deltoids (front of the shoulder), triceps brachii (back of the upper arm), and serratus anterior (the muscles along your ribs that help stabilise the shoulder blade). The Renegade Push-Up also strongly recruits the latissimus dorsi, making it the most complete upper-body exercise in this list.</span></p></div></section><section data-section-id="pf-b1bf" data-pf-type="FlexSection" class="sc-gKlDTn jrBPeP pf-34_ pf-container-1"><div class="sc-jRGIGG bMuAgN pf-flex-section"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cyRdfs qmQNK pf-35_"><strong>Exercise 1: Floor Press</strong></h3></div></section><section data-section-id="pf-0efb" data-pf-type="FlexSection" class="sc-gKlDTn jrBPeP pf-37_ pf-container-1"><div class="sc-jRGIGG bMuAgN pf-flex-section"><img alt="Floor Press.gif__PID:3c769425-344a-4813-bc4f-65f328f06350" src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=2048" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=375 375w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=550 550w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=768 768w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=1024 1024w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=1280 1280w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=1440 1440w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=1680 1680w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=1800 1800w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=1920 1920w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Floor_Press.gif?v=1764313970&width=2048 2048w" fetchPriority="low" decoding="async" loading="lazy" style="--pf-image-ratio:1.775" sizes="75vw" data-pf-type="Image5" class="sc-fscnvs dncZrx pf-38_" store="[object Object]"/></div></section><section data-section-id="pf-dafd" data-pf-type="FlexSection" class="sc-gKlDTn jrBPeP pf-39_ pf-container-1"><div class="sc-jRGIGG bMuAgN pf-flex-section"><p class="sc-hgRQsa gNGIPQ pf-40_" data-pf-type="Paragraph4"><input type="checkbox" id="compact-eedafdc1-c101-44d0-a5e4-2a8df93ddcee"/><span class="pf-paragraph-content "><strong>Why Do It:</strong><br><br>The floor press is the same movement as the dumbbell bench press, except that the floor limits your range of motion. That’s not a problem because <strong>you don’t need to go lower than a 90-degree elbow bend for maximum pec stimulation.</strong> If you do, you run the risk of shoulder joint strain.<br><br>The <strong>floor press allows you to go heavier</strong> than you could with a standard dumbbell bench press. The floor gives you a slight assist, providing a solid platform to press from.<br><br><strong>How To Do It:<br></strong><br>1 -&nbsp;Place a pair of dumbbells on the floor and sit behind them with your knees bent.<br><br>2 - Grab the <strong><span style="background-color: rgba(245, 166, 35, 0.48);"><a href="/collections/adjustable-dumbbells" target="_self"></a></span></strong><span style="background-color: rgba(245, 166, 35, 0.48);"><a href="/collections/adjustable-dumbbells" target="_self"><u><span style="color: rgb(245, 166, 35);">dumbbells</span></u><strong></strong></a></span> and roll back to lie flat on your back with the weights above your chest at arm’s length.<br><br>3 -&nbsp;Face your palms away from you and touch the dumbbells together.<br><br>4 -&nbsp;<strong>Lower the weights under control</strong> until your elbows touch the floor.<br><br>5 -&nbsp;Press back to the starting position.<br><br>Sets &amp; Reps: 3–4 sets | 8–12 reps | Rest: 90 seconds<br>Tip: Keep the dumbbells touching throughout — this keeps tension on the inner chest for the full set.<br></span></p></div></section><section data-section-id="pf-e1d0" data-pf-type="FlexSection" class="sc-gKlDTn jrBPeP pf-43_ pf-container-1 pf-sm-hide pf-hide"><div class="sc-jRGIGG bMuAgN pf-flex-section"><div data-pf-type="FlexBlock" class="sc-fYXHKj TqaeK pf-44_"><div data-pf-type="FlexBlock" class="sc-fYXHKj TqaeK pf-45_"><img alt="Group 25.png__PID:29438d2a-94fd-44ae-8c73-ba96766aa110" src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=2048" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=375 375w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=550 550w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=768 768w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=1024 1024w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=1280 1280w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=1440 1440w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=1680 1680w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=1800 1800w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=1920 1920w,https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/2623/4904/files/Group_25.png?v=1762991593&width=2048 2048w" fetchPriority="low" decoding="async" loading="lazy" style="--pf-image-ratio:1.1754385964912282" sizes="75vw" data-pf-type="Image5" class="sc-fscnvs dncZrx pf-46_" store="[object Object]"/></d